I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data against a schema. Based on the workflow plan, this requires first executing the data_processing_parser.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool to validate the parsed data against a schema, as per the workflow plan.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll execute the final step in the workflow - using the network_poster tool to post the processed data. According to the workflow plan, this requires first executing the data_processing_transformer and integration_authenticator tools.

I'll start with the data_processing_transformer:

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

                        Next, I'll execute the integration_authenticator tool as required before the final network_poster step:

<tool_call>integration_authenticator
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

                        Now I'll execute the final network_poster tool to post the processed data, using the authentication token we just received:

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "auth": {
      "token": "token_750806",
      "type": "Bearer"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
